A spokesperson for German Foreign Minister Sigmar Gabriel said on Monday that German diplomats in Turkey would be granted access to Deniz Yucel, a German-Turkish journalist for the "Welt" newspaper. He has been held since the middle of February and is being accused of supporting terrorism. Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://dw.com/p/2YbaWTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan accused Yucel of "espionage" in a recent speech and said he was an agent of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which is banned in Turkey.Yucel has been taken into pre-trial custody, which can last up to five years in Turkey.Criticism of Yucel's detention has been loud in Germany, with many accusations that it was a politically motivated move designed to sway sympathies toward Erdogan ahead of an April 16 referendum regarding the powers of the president.Turkey is also the most prolific jailer of journalists in the world, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, and the country ranked 151 of 180 in Reporters Without Borders' 2016 edition of the World Press Freedom Index.mz/msh (Reuters, dpa) Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://dw.com/p/2Yy2c